{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533669"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:38:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:38:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14857"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585085"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:02:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:02:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14857"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14857"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.19,0.07,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7548"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7548"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44467"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3232"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5185"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of progressive tremor and stiffness. She has a history of schizophrenia, hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and gastroesophageal reflux disease. Her medications include haloperidol, metoclopramide, prochlorperazine, verapamil, and metformin. She lives independently and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has a resting tremor of both hands, cogwheel rigidity at the wrists, and reduced arm swing when walking. Her gait is slow with short steps.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely to have caused these symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haloperidol","Metoclopramide","Prochlorperazine","Verapamil","Metformin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of drug-induced parkinsonism. The clinical features include resting tremor, cogwheel rigidity, and parkinsonian gait. When evaluating new parkinsonism, particularly in older adults, a medication review is essential as various drugs can cause or exacerbate parkinsonian symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause as it is a first-generation (typical) antipsychotic with strong dopamine D2 receptor antagonism. This high D2 receptor affinity leads to a greater risk of extrapyramidal side effects, including drug-induced parkinsonism. The elderly are particularly susceptible to these effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiemetic that can cause drug-induced parkinsonism through its D2 receptor antagonism. However, its effects are typically less severe than those of antipsychotics, and it is usually prescribed for shorter durations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProchlorperazine\u003C/strong\u003E, while also a phenothiazine with D2 antagonist properties that can cause parkinsonism, is typically used at lower doses and for shorter periods than antipsychotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerapamil\u003C/strong\u003E is a calcium channel blocker that has been rarely associated with drug-induced parkinsonism, but this is much less common than with dopamine antagonists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E can cause vitamin B12 deficiency with long-term use, which may lead to peripheral neuropathy and balance problems, but does not cause parkinsonism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement would involve either reducing the dose of haloperidol or switching to a second-generation antipsychotic with a lower risk of extrapyramidal side effects. Anticholinergic medications may be used for symptomatic relief while making these changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First generation (typical) antipsychotics commonly cause extrapyramidal side effects including parkinsonism.","Drug-induced parkinsonism typically develops within weeks to months of starting or increasing antipsychotic medication.","When evaluating new parkinsonism, review of medications is essential as many drugs can cause or exacerbate symptoms."],"references":["Shin HW, Chung SJ. Drug-induced parkinsonism. Journal of clinical neurology (Seoul, Korea). 2012 Mar 31;8(1):15."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44467"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14857"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44467"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T14:59:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T14:59:3